{
  "texts": [
    "124 Another alternative is to constrain the space of hypotheses.",
    "In the philosophy of induction, this can be motivated on the basis of Occam's razor, which roughly states that simpler hypotheses are generally more better than complex alternatives.",
    "But what does \"simpler\" mean?",
    "And how many samples do we need to infer a simple hypothesis that is able to predict well?",
    "In computational learning theory, such questions can be effectively addressed by the Probably Approximately Correct (PAC) model of learning, introduced by Leslie Valiant (1984)."
  ]
}